{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OppositeTropes"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Contrast}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BeingEvilSucks"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Being Evil Sucks}}. Also, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DownerEnding"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Downer Ending}}, or, if you\'92re lucky, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EarnYourHappyEnding"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Earn Your Happy Ending}}. Compare {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NoGoodDeedGoesUnpunished"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 No Good Deed Goes Unpunished}}, where the good action (rather than the process of being good) is what gets the characters in trouble. May result in someone expressing {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SympathyForTheHero"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Sympathy for the Hero}}. Contrast {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KarmaHoudiniWarranty"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Karma Houdini Warranty}}, where trying to turn over a new leaf can bring down heaven\'92s wrath. This is one way people become an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IronWoobie"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Iron Woobie}} or a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KnightInSourArmor"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Knight In Sour Armor}}, depending on whether the suffering is taken with quiet dignity or grumpy complaining. This belief is the original mentality of a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MoralPragmatist"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Moral Pragmatist}} before a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HeelFaceTurn"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Heel\'96Face Turn}} or someone tries to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CutLexLuthorACheck"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Cut Lex Luthor a Check}}, but they may wind up here again if they\'92re proven right.\
There are many instances in real life in which being \'91good\'92 doesn\'92t suck that much. Scientifically, deeds perceived as good - whether or not they are good - entail social recognition and approval, and bad deeds entail reprisal. Most villains or villainous groups might also view their actions as \'91good\'92 in some sense, however, and therefore it might be unclear that this counts as \'91good\'92 in the same sense as a story with an author-determined moral compass. Justice is one of the fundamental evolutionary imperatives that allows human society to function coherently; we may not all be saints, but we\'92re not all lawless murderers. Unless you\'92re a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainWithGoodPublicity"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Villain with Good Publicity}} It\'92s usually more profitable to abide by society\'92s rules, and even in that case you could be best off being {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AffablyEvil"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Affably Evil}}. However, the more you could influence perception in such a context, the less it would matter here whether or not you were evil. Of course, multiple societies might have different and often conflicting moral codes, even within their own confines; further, if people like Karl Marx (himself a \'91villain\'92 to some, but not all) are to be believed, the conflict within societies can sometimes be such as to give rise to fundamentally opposed forces and force recourse to struggle. Further, moral codes change over time, and this occasionally leads to conflicts between earlier morality and new trends. As a result, a simplistic application of the story-telling categories of \'91villains\'92 and \'91heroes\'92 from fiction to real life might be worth avoiding, when it comes to this trope.}